|url=https://247sports.com/Season/2007-Football/CompositeTeamRankings|publisher=CBS INTERACTIVE|date=2007|title=2007 Football Team Rankings|access-date=3 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mississippistate.247sports.com/Season/2007-Football/Commits|publisher=CBS INTERACTIVE|date=2007|title=Mississippi State 2007 Football Commits|access-date=3 July 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==First round draft picks==\nMississippi State has had 14 players selected in the first round of professional football drafts.\n\n===National Football League===\n{{Div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* 1949 \u2013 [[Harper Davis]]\n* 1956 \u2013 [[Art Davis (American football)|Art Davis]]\n* 1959 \u2013 [[Billy Stacy]]\n* 1975 \u2013 [[Jimmy Webb (American football)|Jimmy Webb]]\n* 1982 \u2013 [[Glen Collins (American football)|Glen Collins]] & [[Johnie Cooks]]\n* 1983 \u2013 [[Michael Haddix]]\n* 1996 \u2013 [[Eric Moulds]] & [[Walt Harris (cornerback)|Walt Harris]]\n* 2011 \u2013 [[Derek Sherrod]]\n* 2012 \u2013 [[Fletcher Cox]]\n* 2019 \u2013 [[Jeffery Simmons]], [[Montez Sweat]] & [[Johnathan Abram]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Coaching staff==\n\n===Head coaches===\n{{Main|List of Mississippi State Bulldogs head football coaches}}\nThe program has had 32&nbsp;head coaches since it began play during the [[1895 college football season|1895 season]], and has played more than 1,050 games over 111 seasons.<ref name=m86>''2011 Mississippi State Football Media Guide'', pp. 86\u201392</ref> From December 2008 though November 2017, [[Dan Mullen]] served as Mississippi State's head coach.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=3760099 |first=Pat |last=Forde |title=Mississippi State hires Florida coordinator as coach |publisher=ESPN.com |date=2008-12-11 |accessdate=2011-07-31}}</ref> Former Washington State head coach Mike Leach is the current head coach for Mississippi State.\n\n===Historic coaching hire===\nMississippi State made history on December 1, 2003, when it hired [[Sylvester Croom]] as its head football coach. Croom was the first African-American named to such a position in the history of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC).{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n== Future opponents ==\n\n=== 2020 Schedule ===\n\n{{CFB schedule\n| opprank = y\n| rankyear = 2020\n| rankdivision = NCAA Division I FBS\n| timezone = Central\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 5\n| time = \n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = [[New Mexico Lobos football|New Mexico]]\n| site_stadium = [[Davis Wade Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Starkville, Mississippi|Starkville, MS]]\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 12\n| time = \n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[NC State Wolfpack football|NC State]]\n| site_stadium = [[Carter\u2013Finley Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh, NC]]\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 19\n| time = \n| nonconf = \n| opponent = [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]]\n| site_stadium = Davis Wade Stadium\n| site_cityst = Starkville, MS\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 26\n| time = \n| nonconf = y \n| opponent = [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]]\n| site_stadium = Davis Wade Stadium\n| site_cityst = Starkville, MS\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 3\n| time = \n| opponent = [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]]\n| site_stadium = Davis Wade Stadium\n| site_cityst = Starkville, MS\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 17\n| time = \n| away = y \n| opponent = [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]]\n| gamename = [[Alabama\u2013Mississippi State football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa, AL]]\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 24\n| time = \n| away = y\n| opponent = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]]\n| gamename = [[LSU\u2013Mississippi State football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = [[Tiger Stadium (LSU)|Tiger Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge, LA]]\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 31\n| time =  \n| opponent = [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]]\n| site_stadium = Davis Wade Stadium\n| site_cityst = Starkville, MS\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 7\n| time = \n| opponent = [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]]\n| site_stadium = Davis Wade Stadium\n| site_cityst = Starkville, MS\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 14\n| time = \n| away = y\n| opponent = [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky]]\n| site_stadium = [[Kroger Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington, KY]]\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 21\n| time = \n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = [[Alabama A&M Bulldogs football|Alabama A&M]]\n| site_stadium = Davis Wade Stadium\n| site_cityst = Starkville, MS\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = {{tooltip|November 26|Thursday}}\n| time =\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]]\n| gamename = [[Egg Bowl]]\n| site_stadium = [[Vaught\u2013Hemingway Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Oxford, Mississippi|Oxford, MS]]\n}}\n}}\n\n===Intra-division opponents===\nMississippi State plays the other six SEC West opponents once per season.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Mississippi State Bulldogs|Even numbered years|Odd number years}}\n|- \n| at [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] || vs Alabama\n|- \n| vs [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]] || at Arkansas\n|- \n| vs [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]] || at Auburn\n|- \n| at [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] || vs LSU\n|- \n| vs [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]] || at Texas A&M\n|- \n| at [[Mississippi Rebels football|Ole Miss]] || vs Ole Miss\n|}\n\n=== Non-division opponents ===\nMississippi State plays Kentucky as a permanent non-division opponent annually and rotates around the ''East'' division among the other six schools.<ref name=\"nondivopp\">{{cite web| title=SEC Future Football Schedule Rotation Announced|publisher=fbschedules.com| url=http://www.fbschedules.com/2014/05/sec-future-football-schedule-rotation-2025/|accessdate=2014-06-14}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Mississippi State Bulldogs |2020|2021|2022|2023|2024|2025}}\n|- \n| at [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky]] || vs Kentucky || at Kentucky || vs Kentucky || at Kentucky || vs Kentucky\n|- \n| vs [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]] || at [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]] || vs [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] || at [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]] || vs [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] || at [[Florida Gators football|Florida]]\n|}\n\n=== Non-conference opponents ===\nAnnounced schedules as of July 5, 2019.<ref name=\"nonconfopp\">{{cite web| title=Mississippi State Bulldogs Football Schedules and Future Schedules|publisher=fbschedules.com| url=http://www.fbschedules.com/ncaa/sec/mississippi-state-bulldogs.php|accessdate=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Mississippi State Bulldogs|2020|2021|2022|2023|2024|2025|2026|2027|2028|2029}}\n|- \n|at [[NC State Wolfpack football|NC State]] || vs [[NC State Wolfpack football|NC State]] || at [[Arizona Wildcats football|Arizona]] || vs [[Arizona Wildcats football|Arizona]] || at [[Arizona State Sun Devils football|Arizona State]] || vs [[Arizona State Sun Devils football|Arizona State]] || at [[Minnesota Golden Gophers football|Minnesota]]  || vs [[Minnesota Golden Gophers football|Minnesota]] || vs [[Texas Tech Red Raiders football|Texas Tech]] || at [[Texas Tech Red Raiders football|Texas Tech]]\n|- \n|vs [[UMass Minutemen football|UMass]] || vs [[Louisiana Tech Bulldogs football|Louisiana Tech]] || vs [[Memphis Tigers football|Memphis]] || at [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]] || vs [[UMass Minutemen football|UMass]] || at [[Southern Miss Golden Eagles football|Southern Miss]] || vs [[Troy Trojans football|Troy]] || at [[Troy Trojans football|Troy]] || ||\n|- \n|vs [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]] || at [[Memphis Tigers football|Memphis]] || vs [[Northwestern State Demons football|Northwestern State]] || vs [[Southern Miss Golden Eagles football|Southern Miss]] || vs [[Eastern Kentucky Colonels football|Eastern Kentucky]] || vs [[Alcorn State Braves football|Alcorn State]] || || || ||\n|- \n|vs [[Alcorn State Braves football|Alcorn State]] || vs [[Eastern Illinois Panthers football|Eastern Illinois]] || || vs [[Southeastern Louisiana Lions football|Southeastern Louisiana]] || || || || || ||\n|}\n\n<nowiki>^</nowiki> The 2019 game against Louisiana will be held at [[Mercedes-Benz Superdome]] in [[New Orleans]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Mississippi State Bulldogs football navbox}}\n{{Mississippi State University}}\n{{Southeastern Conference football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mississippi State Bulldogs Football}}\n[[Category:Mississippi State Bulldogs football|*]]\n[[Category:American football teams established in 1895]]\n[[Category:1895 establishments in Mississippi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox NCAA football school\n| CurrentSeason    = 2020 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team\n| TeamName         = Mississippi State Bulldogs football\n| Image            = Mississippi State Bulldogs logo.svg\n| ImageSize        = 150\n| FirstYear        = 1895\n| AthleticDirector = [[John Cohen (baseball)|John Cohen]]\n| HeadCoach        = [[Mike Leach (American football coach)|Mike Leach]]\n| HeadCoachYear    = 1st\n| HCWins           = 0\n| HCLosses         = 0\n| Stadium          = [[Davis Wade Stadium]]\n| FieldName = Scott Field\n| StadiumBuilt     = 1914\n| StadCapacity     = 61,337\n| StadSurface      = Natural Grass\n| Location         = [[Starkville, Mississippi]]\n| NCAAdivision = I FBS\n| Conference       = [[Southeastern Conference]]\n| ConfDivision     = Western\n| PastAffiliations =\n| WebsiteName      = hailstate.com\n| WebsiteURL       = https://hailstate.com/index.aspx?path=football\n| ATWins           = 569 <!-- As of games through 12/30/19 -->\n| ATLosses         = 585 <!-- As of games through 12/30/19 -->\n| ATTies           = 39\n| BowlWins         = 13\n| BowlLosses       = 10\n| BowlTies         =\n| NatlTitles       =\n| ConfTitles       = 1 (1941)\n| DivTitles        = 1 (1998)\n| Heismans         =\n| AllAmericans     = 2<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/2011/Awards.pdf|title=2011 NCAA Football Records \u2013 Award Winners}}</ref>\n| uniform          = File:Mississippi State FB Unis October 2018.png\n| FightSong        = [[Hail State]]\n| MascotDisplay    = Bully\n| MarchingBand     = [[Famous Maroon Band]]\n| Rivalries        = [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]] ([[Egg Bowl|rivalry]])<br />[[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] ([[LSU\u2013Mississippi State football rivalry|rivalry]])<br />[[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] ([[Alabama\u2013Mississippi State football rivalry|rivalry]])\n}}\n\nThe '''Mississippi State Bulldogs football''' program represents [[Mississippi State University]] (MSU) in the sport of [[American football]]. The Bulldogs compete in the [[Football Bowl Subdivision]] (FBS) of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) and the Western Division of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC). Mississippi State has won one SEC championship in 1941 and a division championship in 1998. The Bulldogs have 16 postseason bowl appearances. The program has produced 38 All-Americans (2 consensus), 171 All-SEC selections, and 124 NFL players (11 first-round draft picks).<ref>http://www.hailstate.com 2008 Mississippi State Football Media Guide: Media Information and Record Book</ref> The Bulldogs\u2019 home stadium, [[Davis Wade Stadium]], is the second oldest in the NCAA Division I FBS.\n\n==History==\n{{Main article|List of Mississippi State Bulldogs football seasons}}\n\n===Early history (1895\u20131955)===\n[[File:Dan Martin.png|thumb|Coach Martin]]\nMississippi State (then known as the Mississippi A&M Aggies) first fielded a football team in [[1895 Mississippi A&M Aggies football team|1895]].<ref name=\"forwhomthecowbelltolls.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.forwhomthecowbelltolls.com/2012/5/13/3016190/mississippi-state-football-history-1895 |title=Counting down the Years of Mississippi State Football: 1895 |publisher=For Whom the Cowbell Tolls |date=2012-05-13 |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> The team was coached by [[W. M. Matthews]].<ref name=\"forwhomthecowbelltolls.com\"/> During his one-season tenure, Matthews posted an overall record of zero wins and two losses (0\u20132).<ref name=\"CFDW\">{{cite web|last=DeLassus |first=David |title=W. M. Matthews Records by Year |publisher=[[College Football Data Warehouse]] |url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_year_by_year.php?coachid=1476 |accessdate=February 19, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106172259/http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_year_by_year.php?coachid=1476 |archivedate=November 6, 2012 }}</ref> He is also credited with the selection of what became the official school colors, [[Maroon (color)|maroon]] and white, prior to the Aggies first game ever played at [[Union University]].<ref>{{cite book |title=A Place Called Mississippi: Collected Narratives |last=Barnwell |first=Marion |year=1997 |publisher=University Press of Mississippi |location=Jackson, Mississippi |isbn=0-87805-964-4 |page=241  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KpV3A6jYTVoC&pg=PA241&lpg=PA241&dq=%22W.+M.+Matthews%22+%22Mississippi%22&source=bl&ots=kdFPQdiMDs&sig=5HdJTq6ocAm3zmqLH47ram3DX0Y&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9wFBT_TKGcG-2gWJxu2cCA&ved=0CEMQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=%22W.%20M.%20Matthews%22%20%22Mississippi%22&f=false |accessdate=February 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=2006 Mississippi State Football Media Guide |editor1-first=Joe |editor1-last=Galbraith |editor2-first=Mike |editor2-last=Nemeth |year=2006 |publisher=EBSCO Media |location=Birmingham, Alabama |page=126 |url=http://www.nmnathletics.com/fls/16800/pdf/fb/fb_06mg_history.pdf?DB_OEM_ID=16800 |accessdate=February 19, 2012 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211012443/http://www.nmnathletics.com/fls/16800/pdf/fb/fb_06mg_history.pdf?DB_OEM_ID=16800 |archivedate=December 11, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n[[Daniel S. Martin]] left rival [[Mississippi Rebels football|Ole Miss]] and served as the Aggies' head football coach from [[1903 Mississippi A&M Aggies football team|1903]]\u2013[[1906 Mississippi A&M Aggies football team|1906]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forwhomthecowbelltolls.com/2012/6/21/3108503/The-history-of-Mississippi-State-MSU-Aggies-Bulldogs-football-the-early-years |title=Mississippi State Football History: 1895-1916 |publisher=For Whom the Cowbell Tolls |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> His final record in Starkville was 10\u201311\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/dan-martin-1.html |title=Dan Martin Coaching Record &#124; College Football at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> [[W. D. Chadwick]] led the Aggies from [[1909 Mississippi A&M Aggies football team|1909]]\u2013[[1913 Mississippi A&M Aggies football team|1913]].<ref name=\"sports-reference.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/william-chadwick-1.html |title=William Chadwick Coaching Record &#124; College Football at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> His final record was 29\u201312\u20132.<ref name=\"sports-reference.com\"/> During his five-season tenure, Mississippi A&M appeared in and won its first bowl game, the [[1911 Mississippi A&M Aggies football team|1911]] [[Bacardi Bowl]] in [[Havana, Cuba]].<ref name=\"sports-reference.com\"/> Fullback [[Paul A. Reule|Dutch Reule]] was selected [[College Football All-Southern Team|All-Southern]]. The 1911 team was also referred to as 'The Bull Dogs'.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/reveille71911miss#page/146/mode/2up |title=Reville Vol VII The Yearbook of the Class of 1911| publisher=Mississippi A&M College |location=Starkville, Mississippi | page=174}}</ref> [[Earle C. Hayes]] replaced Chadwick and led Mississippi A&M to 15\u20138\u20132 record from [[1914 Mississippi A&M Aggies football team|1914]]\u20131916.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/ec-hayes-1.html |title=E.C. Hayes Coaching Record &#124; College Football at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> [[Hunter Kimball]] received the most votes of any All-Southern [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] in 1914.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=omLzAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA33&lpg=PA33&dq=georgia+tech+%22all+southern%22&source=bl&ots=jkaf-RliRx&sig=T_UzhxZts7Pj2kSPWUbgWVvz6fw&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qw8OVKGrF8aWgwTgtYHoAw&ved=0CFwQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Spalding's Official Football Guide|publisher = NCAA |date=1915}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=3s6HVKSxIseZNqOrhPAM&id=hItYAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22reule%22+mississippi+state+football&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22reule%22+|page=40|title=1|journal=The M Book of Athletics, Mississippi A and M College|volume=2|year=1947|author=John Wendell Bailey}}</ref> The Mississippi Legislature renamed Mississippi A&M as \"Mississippi State College\" in 1925 and the mascot was changed from Aggies to Maroons in 1932.<ref name=\"msstate.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hailstate.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=926236|title=Mississippi State Traditions - Mississippi State Athletics|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> [[Ralph Sasse]] enjoyed success as Mississippi State's head football coach. After leading Mississippi State to a 20\u201310\u20132 record in three years and an appearance in the [[1937 Orange Bowl]],<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/ralph-sasse-1.html |title=Ralph Sasse Coaching Record &#124; College Football at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> a loss,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Sasse stunned the students and players by resigning from his head coach's duties, following a doctor's orders after a sudden nervous breakdown.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sasse Confined to Home After Giving Up Post |agency=Associated Press |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=MIUcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YWQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2124%2C2985320 |newspaper=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]] |date=November 11, 1937 |accessdate=February 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Allyn McKeen]] left [[Memphis Tigers football|Memphis]] to become head football coach at Mississippi State,<ref name=\"footballfoundation.org\">{{cite web|url={{College Football HoF/url|id=1624}} |title=Allyn McKeen|work=College Football Hall of Fame|publisher=Footballfoundation.org |date=1991-01-25 |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> where he compiled a 65\u201319\u20133 record in ten seasons.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/allyn-mckeen-1.html |title=Allyn McKeen Coaching Record &#124; College Football at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> In 1940, he was named Southeastern Conference Coach of the Year after leading Mississippi State to its only undefeated season in school history and its second Orange Bowl appearance, a victory.<ref name=\"footballfoundation.org\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> The following year, 1941, his Maroons squad captured the first and only Southeastern Conference championship in program history. McKeen retired from coaching in 1948 after being fired by Athletic Director Dudy Noble because of a 4\u20134\u20131 season.<ref>{{cite book|last=Nemeth|first=Mike|title=Mississippi State Football Vault (College Vault)|year=2009|publisher=Whitman Publishing|isbn=9780794828073}}</ref> He was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] as a coach in 1991. Mississippi State did not field a football team in 1943.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2013/08/sec_football_by_the_numbers_se_1.html |title=SEC Football by the Numbers: Season-opening streaks \u2013 Florida's record roll |publisher=AL.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> [[Arthur Morton (American football)|Arthur Morton]] left [[VMI Keydets football|VMI]] to become MSU's head football coach after McKeen's retirement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1817&dat=19490101&id=DvQ-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=Vk0MAAAAIBAJ&pg=3036,35076|title=The Tuscaloosa News - Google News Archive Search|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> Morton's Maroons posted struggling records of 0\u20138\u20131, 4\u20135 and 4\u20135 for a cumulative record of 8\u201318\u20131<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/slick-morton-1.html |title=Slick Morton Coaching Record &#124; College Football at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> before Morton's firing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PwhmOrF_u7gC&pg=PA142&lpg=PA142&dq=slick+morton+fired+mississippi+state&source=bl&ots=tsJvCaAQ09&sig=TEn0sjCLIruEWl6tAc4pwA8_wzE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2E5pU6GLBLSCyAHD54DIBA&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=slick%20morton%20fired%20mississippi%20state&f=false |title=Maroon and White: Mississippi State University, 1878-2003 - Michael B. Ballard - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> [[Murray Warmath]] came to Mississippi State from his post as line coach at [[Army Cadets football|Army]]<ref name=\"govolsxtra.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.govolsxtra.com/news/2011/mar/18/former-vol-coach-warmath-dies-at-98/ |title=GoVolsXtra, University of Tennessee sports |publisher=Govolsxtra.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> and posted records of 5\u20134 and 5\u20132\u20133 for a cumulative two-season record of 10\u20136\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/murray-warmath-1.html |title=Murray Warmath Coaching Record &#124; College Football at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> Having coached only two seasons in Starkville, Warmath resigned after the 1953 season to take the job of [[Minnesota Golden Gophers football|University of Minnesota]] head coach.<ref name=\"govolsxtra.com\"/>\n\n[[Darrell Royal]] came to Mississippi State from the [[Canadian Football League|CFL]]'s [[Edmonton Eskimos]]<ref name=\"espn.go.com\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/8602286/darrell-royal-former-longhorns-coach-dies-age-88 |title=Darrell Royal, former Longhorns coach, dies at age 88 |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=2012-11-09 |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> and put up back-to-back 6\u20134 records in his two seasons as the Maroons head football coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/darrell-royal-1.html |title=Darrell Royal Coaching Record &#124; College Football at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> Royal resigned after the 1955 season to accept the head football coach position at [[Washington Huskies football|Washington]].<ref name=\"espn.go.com\"/>\n\n===Wade Walker era (1956\u20131961)===\n[[Wade Walker]] was promoted from line coach to head coach following Royal's departure. Walker compiled a 22\u201332\u20132 record over his 6-season tenure.<ref>[http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/CFHSN/CFHSNv07/CFHSNv07n4a.pdf Charles \"Bud\" Wilkinson] (PDF), College Football Historical Society Newsletter, Vol. VII, No. II, August 1994.</ref><ref>[http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_year_by_year.php?coachid=2421 Wade Walker Records by Year] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100215042124/http://cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_year_by_year.php?coachid=2421 |date=2010-02-15 }}, College Football Data Warehouse, retrieved June 17, 2009.</ref> In 1958 the Legislature renamed the university as Mississippi State University. The Mississippi State Maroons posted a lackluster 2\u20137\u20131 record in 1959.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/wade-walker-1.html |title=Wade Walker Coaching Record &#124; College Football at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> The following year, Walker's Maroons improved to 5\u20135,<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> but students, fans and alumni demanded his ouster.<ref name=\"hailstate1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hailstate.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=209350987 |title=Services For Former MSU Coach/Athletic Director Wade Walker Saturday \u2013 Mississippi State University Bulldogs Official Athletic Site |publisher=HailState.com |accessdate=2015-12-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120101200/http://www.hailstate.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=209350987 |archivedate=2016-01-20 }}</ref> University president [[Dean W. Colvard]] relented and fired Walker as football coach, but kept him on as athletic director, a post he kept until 1966.<ref name=\"hailstate1\"/><ref>Michael B. Ballard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=65J5gDduWJ4C ''Maroon and White: Mississippi State University, 1878\u20132003''], p. 144, University Press of Mississippi, 2008, {{ISBN|1-57806-999-8}}.</ref> Mississippi State changed its mascot from Maroons to Bulldogs in 1960.<ref name=\"msstate.edu\"/> However, \"Bulldogs\" had been used unofficially since at least 1905, and the nickname had long been interchangeable with \"Maroons.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hailstate.com/sports/2007/6/19/926236.aspx#bulldog |title=Mississippi State Traditions: The Bulldog |publisher=Mississippi State University |date=n.d. |accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Paul Davis era (1962\u20131966)===\n[[Paul E. Davis|Paul Davis]] was promoted from assistant coach to head coach following Walker's firing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=4033186 |title=Former Mississippi State Bulldogs coach Paul Davis dies at 87 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2009-01-04 |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> His teams went 20\u201338\u20132 overall and 9\u201322\u20132 in the [[Southeastern Conference]] in Davis' five seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/paul-davis-2.html |title=Paul Davis Coaching Record &#124; College Football at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-12}}</ref> The Bulldogs had a 7\u20132\u20132 record in 1963, earning its first postseason bowl game since 1939.<ref name=KnoxvilleObit>Strange, Mike. [http://www.knoxnews.com/news/2009/mar/31/davis-former-sec-coach-dies-at-87/ \"Davis, former SEC coach, dies at 87\"], ''[[Knoxville News Sentinel]]'', March 31, 2009. Accessed April 6, 2009.</ref> The team finished the season with a 16\u201312 victory over [[NC State Wolfpack football|North Carolina State]] in front of 8,309 fans at the [[1963 Liberty Bowl]] played in a bitter cold [[Philadelphia]].<ref name=APObit>via ''[[Associated Press]]'. [http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=4033186 \"Ex-Bulldogs coach Davis dies at 87\"], ''[[ESPN]]'', April 1, 2009. Accessed April 1, 2009.</ref> Mississippi State was able to convert two botched North Carolina State punts into touchdowns, and a 13\u20130 lead at the first quarter.<ref>White, Gordon S.. Jr. [https://www.nytimes.com/1963/12/22/archives/n-carolina-state-bows-miss-states-early-attack-tops-nc-state-in.html \"N. Carolina State Bows; Miss. State's Early Attack Tops N.C. State in Liberty Bowl, 16\u201312 Ball Barely Reaches Long March Starts\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 22, 1963. Accessed April 6, 2009.</ref> [[United Press International]] named Davis the [[Southeastern Conference football individual awards#Coach of the Year|SEC Coach of the Year]] for the 1963 season.<ref name=KnoxvilleObit/> After a lackluster 2\u20138 record in 1966, MSU terminated Davis, as well as athletic director Wade Walker.<ref>Via [[Associated Press]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/1966/12/11/archives/football-athletic-heads-out-at-mississippi-state.html \"Football, Athletic Heads Out at Mississippi State\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 11, 1966. Accessed April 6, 2009.</ref>\n\n===Charles Shira era (1967\u20131972)===\n[[Charles Shira]], who had been defensive coordinator for the [[Texas Longhorns football|University of Texas]] under former Bulldogs head coach [[Darrell Royal]], was named to fill the head coaching position as well as the vacant post of Athletic Director.<ref>via ''[[United Press International]]''. [https://www.nytimes.com/1967/01/12/archives/shira-gets-two-posts-at-mississippi-state.html \"Shira Gets Two Posts At Mississippi State\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 12, 1967. Accessed April 6, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn his first season, his team won two games, followed by none the following year. Mississippi State improved to 3\u20137 in 1969. That year, Shira served as the coach for the Gray squad in the [[Blue-Gray Classic]].<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=bPYeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-YwEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1683,5143454&dq=charles-shira&hl=en 32nd Blue-Gray Tilt Set in Montgomery], ''Sarasota Journal'', December 26, 1969.</ref> Mississippi State posted a surprising six-win season in 1970, including a victory over rival #10 [[Mississippi Rebels football|Ole Miss]].<ref name=\"sports-reference1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/charles-shira-1.html|title=Charles Shira Coaching Record - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> For the accomplishment, the SEC named Shira its [[Southeastern Conference football individual awards#Coach of the Year|Coach of the Year]].<ref name=maroon>Michael B. Ballard, [https://books.google.com/books?id=65J5gDduWJ4C ''Maroon and White: Mississippi State University, 1878\u20132003''], p. 201, University Press of Mississippi, 2008, {{ISBN|1-57806-999-8}}.</ref> In 1969, Shira became the first MSU football coach to coach a black player, [[Frank Dowsing]].<ref name=\"Dowsing\">{{cite web |title=Frank Dedric Dowsing, Jr. |url=https://msfame.com/hall-of-fame/inductees/frank-dedric-dowsing-jr/ |website=Mississippi Sports Hall of Fame |access-date=November 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724215248/https://msfame.com/hall-of-fame/inductees/frank-dedric-dowsing-jr/ |archive-date=July 24, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1972, having compiled a record of 16\u201345\u20132,<ref name=\"sports-reference1\"/> Shira resigned as head coach to focus on his duties as athletic director.<ref name=funeral>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4hwsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LckEAAAAIBAJ&pg=971,547209&dq=mississippi-state+athletic-director&hl=en Burial to be in Starkville; Shira Funeral Services Today], ''Florence Times-Tri Cities Daily'', January 3, 1976.</ref>\n\n===Bob Tyler era (1973\u20131978)===\n[[Bob Tyler]] was promoted from offensive coordinator to head coach of the Bulldogs football team after Shira's resignation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://coachingroots.com/football/coaches/bob-tyler |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-05-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140506231732/http://coachingroots.com/football/coaches/bob-tyler |archivedate=2014-05-06 }}</ref> Tyler led Mississippi State to a 9\u20133 season and a victory in the 1974 [[Sun Bowl]] over [[North Carolina Tar Heels football|North Carolina]].<ref name=\"sports-reference2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/bob-tyler-1.html|title=Bob Tyler Coaching Record - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> During that season, his team beat perennial powerhouses, [[1974 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]] and [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/mississippi-state/1973-schedule.html|title=1973 Mississippi State Bulldogs Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> The Bulldogs' record was 6\u20134\u20131 in 1975, and it was an impressive 9\u20132 in 1976, ending the season ranked #20 in the [[AP Poll]].<ref name=\"sports-reference2\"/>  His team compiled a 5\u20136 record in 1977, and he went 6\u20135 in his final season with the Bulldogs.<ref name=\"sports-reference2\"/>\n\nMississippi State was placed on probation by the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA prior]] to the 1975 season due to alleged improper benefits to student athletes.<ref name=\"news.google.com\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1891&dat=19750917&id=rqgfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=aNYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2804,2840175|title=Gadsden Times - Google News Archive Search|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> The school sought and won court approval to play in an adverse legal opinion to the NCAA.<ref name=\"news.google.com\"/> Although the alleged infraction was trivial,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leagle.com/decision/19771424352So2d1072_11393|title=NATIONAL COLLEGIATE ATHLETIC ASS'N v. GILLARD - 352 So.2d 1072 (1977) - Leagle.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> the NCAA forced the school to forfeit most games it won in 1975, 1976, and 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web1.ncaa.org/LSDBi/exec/miSearch?miSearchSubmit=publicReport&key=293&publicTerms=THIS%20PHRASE%20WILL%20NOT%20BE%20REPEATED|title=Legislative Services Database - LSDBi|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Emory Bellard era (1979\u20131985)===\n[[Emory Bellard]], who had resigned as head coach of [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]] during the 1978 season after only six games, was hired to serve as head football coach at Mississippi State beginning with the next (1979) season.<ref name=\"mysanantonio.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/sports/article/Ex-Aggies-football-coach-Emory-Bellard-dies-at-83-1007140.php|title=Ex-Aggies football coach Emory Bellard dies at 83|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> He was head coach from 1979 until 1985.<ref name=\"sports-reference3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/emory-bellard-1.html|title=Emory Bellard Coaching Record - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was considered to have had one of the most innovative offensive minds in football and is credited for inventing the wishbone formation.<ref name=\"mysanantonio.com\"/> Bellard spent seven seasons as head coach at MSU.<ref name=\"sports-reference3\"/> His best years as the Bulldogs head coach were in 1980 and 1981, when his team finished 9\u20133 and 8\u20134, respectively.<ref name=\"sports-reference3\"/> Also, Bellard was the coach when Mississippi State defeated number 1, undefeated [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] 6\u20133 in [[Jackson, Mississippi]], in 1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/mississippi-state/1980-schedule.html|title=1980 Mississippi State Bulldogs Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> \n\nHowever, the Bulldogs significantly regressed after 1981. In the next five seasons, he only won a total of five games in SEC play. Before the 1985 season, Bellard boldly predicted that the Bulldogs would rebound and win their first SEC title since 1941. They not only failed to do so, but went winless in SEC play. Bellard was fired after the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1985-11-28/sports/sp-9173_1_mississippi-state|title=Mississippi State's Bellard Fired as Coach, Forecaster|author1=Times Wire Services|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 11, 1985}}</ref> He would, however, return in 1988 to coach at the high school level in Texas.\n\n===Rockey Felker era (1986\u20131990)===\n[[Rockey Felker]] returned to his alma mater, which was coming off four consecutive losing seasons, from his post as wide receivers coach at [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]].<ref name=\"starkvilledailynews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.starkvilledailynews.com/content/felker-enters-fifth-decade-msu-football|title=Felker enters fifth decade with MSU football - Starkville Daily News|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140507033711/http://www.starkvilledailynews.com/content/felker-enters-fifth-decade-msu-football|archive-date=May 7, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> At 33, Felker was the youngest coach in the country and the first Mississippi State coach in 30 years to start his career as MSU head football coach with a winning record (6\u20135).<ref name=\"starkvilledailynews.com\"/><ref name=\"sports-reference4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/rockey-felker-1.html|title=Rockey Felker Coaching Record - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the Bulldogs never recovered from four consecutive blowout losses at the end of the 1986 season, during which they scored a total of nine points, including a 24-3 loss to Ole Miss.  Felker suffered through four losing seasons (4\u20137, 1\u201310, 5\u20136, 5\u20136) between 1987 and 1990, and only won a total of five games in SEC play. He was only 1-4 vs. Ole Miss.<ref name=\"sports-reference4\"/> He resigned under pressure at the end of the 1990 season,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1320&dat=19901127&id=6MpWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QOoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2643,9702318|title=Gainesville Sun - Google News Archive Search|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> but would be brought back by his successor, [[Jackie Sherrill]], as running backs coach for two seasons and in a non-coaching position in the football program, where he serves to this day.<ref name=\"starkvilledailynews.com\"/>\n\n===Jackie Sherrill era (1991\u20132003)===\nAfter three years away from the game, former [[Washington State Cougars football|Washington State]], [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh]] and [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]] head football coach [[Jackie Sherrill]] was hired as head football coach at Mississippi State in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1990-12-10/sports/sp-4609_1_mississippi-state|title=Mississippi State Hires Sherrill|date=10 December 1990|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017|via=LA Times}}</ref> He took over a program that hadn't had a winning season since 1986 (and had won a total of 14 games in that stretch) and hadn't had a winning record in Southeastern Conference play since 1981. Sherrill began his Mississippi State career with an upset victory over a familiar foe from his A&M days, the Texas Longhorns (who were the defending Southwest Conference champions).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/mississippi-state/1991-schedule.html|title=1991 Mississippi State Bulldogs Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn thirteen seasons in Starkville, Sherrill coached the Bulldogs to a record of 75\u201375\u20132.<ref name=\"sports-reference5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/jackie-sherrill-1.html|title=Jackie Sherrill Coaching Record - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> His 75 wins are the most in school history.  He led the team to an SEC West title in 1998, and a berth in the [[1999 Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton Bowl Classic]].<ref name=\"sports-reference5\"/> A year later, he notched a 10\u20132 record and #12 final ranking.<ref name=\"sports-reference5\"/> That #12 ranking was the highest final ranking achieved by any NCAA Division I-A school in Mississippi in over 30 years.  Sherrill, along with [[Bill Snyder]] of [[Kansas State Wildcats football|Kansas State]], were among the first to use the rich JUCO systems of their respective states to help their programs progress. Although Sherrill won only eight games in his last three seasons, he built Mississippi State into a consistent winner despite playing in the same division as powerhouses like Alabama, Auburn and [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]]. He also finished with a winning record against in-state rival Ole Miss (7\u20136).  Under Sherrill, the Bulldogs went to six bowl games;<ref name=\"sports-reference5\"/> before his arrival they'd only been to seven bowls in 96 years of play.\n\nSherrill also achieved notoriety by having his team observe the castration of a bull as a motivational technique prior to a game versus [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]]. Unranked Mississippi State subsequently beat the #13 ranked Longhorns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/09/16/sports/sports-people-college-football-sherrill-apologizes-for-incident.html|title=SPORTS PEOPLE: COLLEGE FOOTBALL; Sherrill Apologizes for Incident|date=16 September 1992|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Sherrill retired after the 2003 season,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?id=1640479|title=Mississippi State's Jackie Sherrill to retire at end of season|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> which was followed by the NCAA levying probation for four years on the program.<ref name=\"sports.chron.com\">[http://sports.chron.com/default.asp?c=chron&page=cfoot/news/AFN3570480.htm Mississippi State penalized for violations in football]{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Despite a prolonged 3-year investigation by the NCAA, Mississippi State was<ref name=\"sports.espn.go.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/news/story?id=1910571|title=Bad Dogs: Mississippi St. gets probation, more|date=27 October 2004|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> not found guilty of any major violations, and Sherrill was never personally found guilty of any NCAA rules violations at either Mississippi State or Texas A&M.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\n===Sylvester Croom era (2004\u20132008)===\n[[File:Sylvester Croom in 2014.jpg|thumb|Coach Croom]]\n{{very long section|date=April 2018}}\n[[Sylvester Croom]], a longtime assistant in the [[National Football League|NFL]], was hired to replace Sherrill.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/12/01/sports/ncaafootball/01CND-CROOM.html|title=Mississippi St. Hires S.E.C.\u2019s First Black Head Coach|first=Ray|last=Glier|date=1 December 2003|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Croom is a significant figure, because he is not only the first [[African American]] head football coach in Mississippi State history, but also in SEC football history.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> When Croom was hired at Mississippi State, he inherited a program that was riddled with NCAA sanctions and had not won consistently since the 1990s.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nCroom led the Bulldogs to a 3\u20138 (2\u20136 SEC) record in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/mississippi-state/2004-schedule.html |title=2004 Mississippi State Bulldogs Schedule and Results &#124; College Football at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> State began the season with a victory over [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/ncf/recap/_/id/242480344 |title=Tulane vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - September 4, 2004 |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-09-05 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> then lost five straight, to No. 18 [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=242550344 |title=Auburn vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - September 11, 2004 |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-09-11 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> [[Maine Black Bears football|Maine]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=242620344 |title=Maine vs. Mississippi State - Game Summary - September 18, 2004 |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-09-18 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> No. 13 [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=242690099 |title=Mississippi State vs. LSU - Game Recap - September 25, 2004 |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-09-25 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/ncf/recap/_/id/242760238 |title=Mississippi State vs. Vanderbilt - Game Recap - October 2, 2004 |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-10-02 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> and [[UAB Blazers football|UAB]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/ncf/recap/_/id/242830344 |title=UAB vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - October 9, 2004 |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-10-09 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> The next week, State upset No. 20 [[Florida Gators football|Florida]] in what turned out to be the game that got Florida head coach [[Ron Zook]] fired.<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=242970344 |title=Florida vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - October 23, 2004 |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-10-24 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/news/story?id=1908871 |title=With Zook out, will Spurrier get a call? |publisher=Espn.com |date=2004-10-26 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> The next game saw State beat [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/ncf/recap/_/id/243040344 |title=Kentucky vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - October 30, 2004 |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-10-30 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> State then lost their final three games of the season to [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/ncf/recap/_/id/243110333 |title=Mississippi State vs. Alabama - Game Recap - November 6, 2004 |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-11-06 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/ncf/recap/_/id/243250344 |title=Arkansas vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - November 20, 2004 |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-11-22 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> and [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=243320145 |title=Mississippi State vs. Ole Miss - Game Recap - November 27, 2004 |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-11-27 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, State again finished 3\u20138.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/mississippi-state/2005-schedule.html |title=2005 Mississippi State Bulldogs Schedule and Results &#124; College Football at |publisher=Sports-reference.com |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> After defeating [[Murray State Racers football|Murray State]] in the season opener,<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/ncf/recap/_/id/252460344 |title=Murray State vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - September 3, 2005 |publisher=ESPN |date=2005-09-03 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> State lost to [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/ncf/recap/_/id/252530002 |title=Mississippi State vs. Auburn - Game Recap - September 10, 2005 |publisher=ESPN |date=2005-09-10 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> then beat [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]] in [[Shreveport, Louisiana]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/ncf/recap/_/id/252602655 |title=Mississippi State vs. Tulane - Game Recap - September 17, 2005 |publisher=ESPN |date=2005-09-18 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> State then lost seven consecutive games, starting with No. 7 [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=252670344 |title=Georgia vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - September 24, 2005 |publisher=ESPN |date=2005-09-25 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> then No. 4 [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=252740344 |title=LSU vs. Mississippi State - Game Summary - October 1, 2005 |publisher=ESPN |date=2005-10-01 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> No. 13 [[Florida Gators football|Florida]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Final |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=252810057 |title=Mississippi State vs. Florida - Game Recap - October 8, 2005 |publisher=ESPN |date=2005-10-08 |accessdate=2017-05-25}}</ref> [[Houston Cougars football|Houston]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/ncf/recap/_/id/252950344|title=Houston vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - October 22, 2005 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/ncf/recap/_/id/253020096|title=Mississippi State vs. Kentucky - Game Recap - October 29, 2005 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> No. 4 [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=253090344|title=Alabama vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - November 5, 2005 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> and [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/ncf/recap/_/id/253230008|title=Mississippi State vs. Arkansas - Game Recap - November 19, 2005 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> State defeated [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]] in the [[Egg Bowl]] to finish the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=253300344|title=Ole Miss vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - November 26, 2005 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\nMississippi State struggled to a 3\u20139 record in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/mississippi-state/2006-schedule.html|title=2006 Mississippi State Bulldogs Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref> State lost its first three games of the season to [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=262430344|title=South Carolina vs. Mississippi State - Game Summary - August 31, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> No. 4 [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=262520344|title=Auburn vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - September 9, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=262590344|title=Tulane vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - September 16, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> State beat [[UAB Blazers football|UAB]] to get its first win of the year in the fourth game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=262660005|title=Mississippi State vs. UAB - Game Recap - September 23, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> Losses to No 9 [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] and No. 4 [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]] followed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=262730099|title=Mississippi State vs. LSU - Game Recap - September 30, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=262800344|title=West Virginia vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - October 7, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> then State defeated [[Jacksonville State Gamecocks football|Jacksonville State]] to snap the two-game skid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=262870344|title=Jacksonville State vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - October 14, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> State then lost to [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=262940061|title=Mississippi State vs. Georgia - Game Summary - October 21, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> and [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/college-football/recap?gameId=263010344|title=Kentucky vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - October 28, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> MSST then upset [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Alabama]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=263080333|title=Mississippi State vs. Alabama - Game Recap - November 4, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> before losing to No. 5 [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=263220344|title=Arkansas vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - November 18, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> and [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=263290145|title=Mississippi State vs. Ole Miss - Game Summary - November 25, 2006 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2007 season, during which his team won eight games, including the [[Liberty Bowl]],<ref name=\"sports-reference6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/sylvester-croom-1.html|title=Sylvester Croom Coaching Record - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> Croom garnered Coach of the Year awards from three organizations.<ref name=\"sports-reference6\"/> On December 4, 2007, Croom was named coach of the year by the [[American Football Coaches Association]] for region two.<ref name=\"sports-reference6\"/> The AFCA has five regional coaches of the year and announces a national coach of the year each January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarionledger.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071204/SPORTS030102/71204008 |title=Croom receives AFCA regional award |publisher=The ClarionLedger |date= |accessdate=2012-10-23}}</ref> That same year, on December 5, Croom was named SEC Coach of the Year twice, once as voted by the other SEC coaches and once as voted by [[The Associated Press]]. It was the first time a Mississippi State coach received the AP honor since [[Charley Shira]] in 1970 and the first time a Mississippi State coach received the coaches award since [[Wade Walker]] in 1957.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarionledger.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071206/SPORTS030102/712060367/0/SPORTS |title=Croom named SEC's best; Coach honored by conference, media |publisher=The ClarionLedger |date= |accessdate=2012-10-23}}</ref> After a 4\u20138 record in 2008,<ref name=\"sports-reference6\"/> culminating with a 45\u20130 loss to rival #25 [[Mississippi Rebels football|Ole Miss]], Croom was asked by school officials to resign as head coach of the Bulldogs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://djournal.com/view/full_story/20245356/article-ESPN-film-examines--Croom-s-legacy--as-MSU-head-coach |title=ESPN film examines Croom s legacy as MSU head coach |publisher=djournal.com |accessdate=2012-10-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130121150212/http://djournal.com/view/full_story/20245356/article-ESPN-film-examines--Croom-s-legacy--as-MSU-head-coach |archivedate=2013-01-21 }}</ref>\n\n===Dan Mullen era (2009\u20132017)===\n{{very long section|date=April 2018}}\n[[Florida Gators football|Florida]] offensive coordinator [[Dan Mullen]] was hired as Mississippi State's head coach in late 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/news/story?id=3760099|title=Florida assistant Mullen gets Mississippi St. job|date=11 December 2008|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> Mullen arrived in Starkville with an explosive offensive background and a reputation as a quarterback guru, having tutored [[Alex Smith]], [[Chris Leak]] and [[Tim Tebow]] during his career as an assistant coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.usatoday.com/2015/11/30/its-easy-to-see-why-rumors-surround-dan-mullen-annually/|title=It's easy to see why rumors surround Dan Mullen annually|date=30 November 2015|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> Serving under head coach [[Urban Meyer]], Mullen oversaw an offense at Florida that was one of the most explosive in the country, helped the Gators capture the 2006 and 2008 national championships and sent many players into the [[National Football League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.saturdaydownsouth.com/coaches/dan-mullen/|title=Dan Mullen|date=9 July 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2266987-dan-mullen-why-he-should-resist-florida-urge-stay-in-starkville|title=Dan Mullen: Why He Should Resist Florida Urge, Stay in Starkville|first=Heath|last=Clary|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn Mullen's first season, the Bulldogs finished 5\u20137, ending upbeat with a 41\u201327 victory over #20 Ole Miss in the Egg Bowl.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/mississippi-state/2009.html|title=2009 Mississippi State Bulldogs Stats - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> In 2010, they started 1\u20132, and then they had a 6-game winning streak to make their record 7\u20132 before losing to [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] and [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]], but defeated [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]].<ref name=\"sports-reference7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/mississippi-state/2010.html|title=2010 Mississippi State Bulldogs Stats - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> The team participated in a bowl game for the first time since 2007, soundly defeating [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]] in the Gator Bowl 52\u201314.<ref name=\"sports-reference7\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=310010130|title=Mississippi State vs. Michigan - Game Recap - January 1, 2011 - ESPN|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> In 2011, the Bulldogs entered the season ranked #19 in the country, and they started 1\u20130, before losing to the defending national champion [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]] 41\u201334.<ref name=\"sports-reference8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/mississippi-state/2011-schedule.html|title=2011 Mississippi State Bulldogs Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> Mississippi State entered the Ole Miss game in Starkville needing a win to qualify for a bowl bid for a second straight season.<ref name=\"sports-reference8\"/> The Bulldogs won 31\u20133, earning Mullen the distinction as the first coach to beat Ole Miss in his first three tries since Allyn McKeen in 1941.  The Bulldogs capped off the season with a Music City Bowl win over [[Wake Forest Demon Deacons football|Wake Forest]] in Nashville, Tennessee.<ref name=\"sports-reference8\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=313640154|title=Mississippi State vs. Wake Forest - Game Recap - December 30, 2011 - ESPN|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Mississippi State defeated [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] 41\u201331 in their sixth game of the season to become bowl eligible.<ref name=\"sports-reference9\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/mississippi-state/2012-schedule.html|title=2012 Mississippi State Bulldogs Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> After a 7\u20130 start the team won only one of its remaining five games to finish 8\u20135, including a 41-24 loss at Ole Miss and a 34-20 loss to the #21 [[Northwestern Wildcats football|Northwestern]] in the Gator Bowl.<ref name=\"sports-reference9\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=330010077|title=Mississippi State vs. Northwestern - Game Recap - January 1, 2013 - ESPN|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> This was the first time Mississippi State appeared in a bowl three straight years since 2000. In 2013, MSST under Mullen became bowl eligible for the fourth consecutive year following a 17-10 overtime win over Ole Miss.<ref name=\"sports-reference10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/mississippi-state/2013-schedule.html|title=2013 Mississippi State Bulldogs Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> MSST defeated [[Rice Owls football|Rice]] in the [[Liberty Bowl]] December 31, 2013 in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], by a score of 44\u20137.<ref name=\"sports-reference10\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=333650344|title=Rice vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - December 31, 2013 - ESPN|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> It was MSST's third bowl win in the last four years.<ref name=\"hailstate.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hailstate.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=16800&ATCLID=209335516|title=Mississippi State Dominates Rice 44-7 For 2013 Liberty Bowl Title|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n2014 turned out to be the most historic run for the team. Led by quarterback [[Dak Prescott]], the Bulldogs reached a #1 national ranking for the first time ever, doing so in both the Amway [[Coaches Poll]] and the [[AP Poll]], after beating 3 consecutive top-10 teams (#7 [[LSU Tigers]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400548386|title=Mississippi State vs. LSU - Game Recap - September 20, 2014 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> #6 [[Texas A&M Aggies]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400548377|title=Texas A&M vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - October 4, 2014 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> and #2 [[Auburn Tigers]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400548369|title=Auburn vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - October 11, 2014 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> As a result, the Bulldogs became the fastest team in AP Poll's history to reach the #1 ranking, from being unranked, in only 5 weeks. They also became the first team to be ranked #1 in the new FBS Playoff Football Poll and held the top ranking for the first three weeks of the poll before losing to Alabama. However, at the end of the season, only one of the three teams remained ranked. Auburn finished 8\u20135 (4\u20134 SEC) and ranked #22, and lost to [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin]] in the [[Outback Bowl]], [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]] finished 7-5 (3-5 SEC) and beat [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]] in the [[Liberty Bowl]], and [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]], finished 8-4 (4-4 SEC) and lost to [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame]] in the [[Music City Bowl]].<ref name=\"ncaa.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/poll-position/2014-10-12/mississippi-state-completes-fastest-ascent-no-1-ap-top-25|title=Mississippi State completes fastest ascent to No. 1 in AP Top 25 history|date=12 October 2014|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/11688921/mississippi-state-bulldogs-rise-no-1-associated-press-college-football-poll|title=Mississippi St. leaps FSU for No. 1 in AP poll|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref> The Bulldogs couldn't sustain that momentum, and lost two of their last three regular season games, first to #5 [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] 25\u201320<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400548338|title=Mississippi State vs. Alabama - Game Recap - November 15, 2014 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> and then two weeks later to #18 [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]] 31\u201317.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400548324|title=Mississippi State vs. Ole Miss - Game Recap - November 29, 2014 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> That loss knocked the Bulldogs out of playoff contention, leaving them 10\u20132 and ranked #7 by the [[College Football Playoff]] Committee in their final rankings. As a result, they were awarded a trip to the [[Orange Bowl]] against #10 [[Georgia Tech]] on December 31, 2014. Thanks to the Bulldogs\u2019 inability to stop Georgia Tech\u2019s heavy use of the triple option, State lost that contest 49-34. Mississippi State finished the season 10\u20133 and were ranked #11 in the final AP Poll.<ref name=\"cfp-cms-s3-prod.slcfp.com\">{{cite web|url=http://cfp-cms-s3-prod.slcfp.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/CFP-Final-Top-25.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-01-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141211011715/http://cfp-cms-s3-prod.slcfp.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/CFP-Final-Top-25.pdf |archivedate=2014-12-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400610180|title=Mississippi State vs. Georgia Tech - Game Recap - December 31, 2014 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the Bulldogs went 4\u20134 in the SEC and finished the regular season with an 8\u20134 record and went on to play in the [[2015 Belk Bowl]] against the [[2015 NC State Wolfpack football team|NC State Wolfpack]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/mississippi-state/2015-schedule.html|title=2015 Mississippi State Bulldogs Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref> winning 51-28.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400852728|title=NC State vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - December 30, 2015 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> [[Dak Prescott]] was named the game MVP after throwing 4 touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ktbs.com/story/30857864/dak-prescott-puts-exclamation-point-on-career-wins-belk-bowl-mvp|title=Dak Prescott puts exclamation point on career, wins Belk Bowl MVP|first=Alex|last=Anderson|publisher=}}</ref> 2016 saw the Bulldogs stumble to a 5\u20137 regular season record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/mississippi-state/2016-schedule.html|title=2016 Mississippi State Bulldogs Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref> The season included 3 losses on the final play of games against [[South Alabama Jaguars football|South Alabama]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400868975|title=South Alabama vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - September 3, 2016 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> [[BYU Cougars football|BYU]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400868928|title=Mississippi State vs. BYU - Game Recap - October 14, 2016 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> and [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400869031|title=Mississippi State vs. Kentucky - Game Recap - October 22, 2016 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> The Bulldogs were able to finish the season on a high note defeating in-state rival Ole Miss 55-20 in the 2016 [[Egg Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400869072|title=Mississippi State vs. Ole Miss - Game Recap - November 26, 2016 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> Due to a shortage of 6-win teams and MSU's [[Academic Progress Rate]], they made their seventh consecutive bowl appearance in the [[St. Petersburg Bowl]] against [[Miami RedHawks football|Miami (OH)]] on December 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/college-football-2016-bowl-eligibility-75-teams-qualify-leaving-five-open-spots/|title=College football 2016 bowl eligibility: 75 teams qualify, leaving five open spots|publisher=}}</ref> The Bulldogs won the game thanks to a blocked extra point and a blocked field goal, edging Miami (Ohio) 17-16.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400876090|title=Miami (OH) vs. Mississippi State - Game Recap - December 26, 2016 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> On February 27, 2017, Mississippi State athletic director [[John Cohen (baseball)|John Cohen]] announced a four-year contract extension for Coach Mullen through February 2021.<ref>{{cite web |title=MSU announces 4-year coach extension|url=http://hailstate.com/news/2017/2/27/football-msu-announces-four-year-contract-extension-for-dan-mullen.aspx|publisher=HailState.com|year=2017|accessdate=February 28, 2017}}</ref> In November 2017, after an 8-4 season, Dan Mullen left Mississippi State University to become the head coach at the University of Florida.\n\n===Joe Moorhead era (2018\u20132019)===\nAfter [[Dan Mullen]]\u2019s departure, Mississippi State hired  [[Penn State Nittany Lions football|Penn State]] offensive coordinator [[Joe Moorhead]] as the program's 33rd head coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/21603052|title=Miss. St. hands reins to 'blue-collar' Moorhead|date=November 29, 2017|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> Moorhead arrived in Starkville with a reputation as an outstanding offensive mind, turning around a struggling [[Football Championship Subdivision|FCS]] program in [[Fordham Rams football|Fordham]] as the head coach before moving to Penn State as offensive coordinator where his offenses set school records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hailstate.com/news/2017/11/29/joe-moorhead-named-mississippi-states-33rd-head-football-coach.aspx|title=Joe Moorhead Named Mississippi State's 33rd Head Football Coach|website=Mississippi State}}</ref> The Mississippi State University administration signed Moorhead to a four-year contract worth a total of $11 million in base salary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.djournal.com/sports/msu-notebook-moorhead-s-modest-contract-means-more-money-for/article_a68d710e-be7d-5c99-ad25-b5b03dcdc21e.html|title=MSU Notebook: Moorhead's modest contract means more money for staff|first=Logan Lowery Daily|last=Journal|website=Daily Journal}}</ref>\n\nOn January 3, 2020, after failing to energize the offense, and several off field issues, Mississippi State announced Moorhead's firing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hailstate.com/news/2020/1/3/joe-moorhead-relieved-of-duties-as-head-football-coach.aspx|title=Joe Moorhead Relieved of Duties as Head Football Coach|date=January 3, 2020|website=Mississippi State}}</ref>\n\n===Mike Leach era (2020\u2013)===\nOn January 9, 2020, Mississippi State athletic director [[John Cohen (baseball)|John Cohen]] announced the hiring of then-[[Washington State Cougars football|Washington State]] and former-[[Texas Tech]] head coach [[Mike Leach (American football coach)|Mike Leach]] to the vacant head coaching position.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thespun.com/sec/mississippi-state/mississippi-state-coaching-search-todd-grantham-joe-judge-giants|title=Mike Leach Leaves Washington State for Mississippi State|date=January 9, 2020|website=ESPN}}</ref>\n\n== Conference affiliations ==\n* Independent (1895)\n* [[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association]] (1896\u20131921).<ref name=\"handbook\">{{cite book |title=Handbook of Southern Intercollegiate Track and Field Athletics |last=Bailey |first=John Wendell |year=1924 |publisher=Mississippi Agricultural and Mechanical College |page=14 }}</ref>\n* [[Southern Conference]] (1922\u20131932)<ref>[http://www.soconsports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?&DB_OEM_ID=4000&ATCLID=177772&SPID=3001&SPSID=69769 The Southern Conference]</ref>\n* [[Southeastern Conference]] (1933\u2013present)\n\n== Championship ==\n=== Conference championship ===\nThe 1941 Mississippi State Bulldogs finished the year with an 8\u20131\u20131 record, and won the Southeastern Conference championship. The season included wins over Florida, Alabama, Auburn, and Ole Miss. The Bulldogs tied with LSU and were defeated by [[Duquesne Dukes football|Duquesne]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Mississippi State Bulldogs|Season|Conference|Coach|Overall record|Conference record}}\n|-\n| [[1941 Mississippi State Maroons football team|1941]] || SEC || [[Allyn McKeen]] || 8\u20131\u20131 || 4\u20130\u20131\n|}\n\n=== Division championship ===\nThe SEC has been split into two divisions since the 1992 season with Mississippi State competing in the SEC West since that time. In 1998, MSU finished the regular season with a 26\u201314 win over Alabama, a 22\u201321 win over [[Arkansas]], and a 28\u20136 win over Ole Miss in Oxford, Mississippi. At the end of the regular season, both MSU and Arkansas finished with 6\u20132 conference records, but by virtue of MSU's head-to-head win over Arkansas, MSU earned the right to represent the SEC West in the [[1998 SEC Championship Game|SEC Championship Game]]. In that game, MSU led eventual national champion [[1998 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]] in the fourth quarter before falling 14\u201324 in the [[Georgia Dome]]. They continued on to play in the [[1999 Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton Bowl Classic]] in Dallas, Texas, against the 20th-ranked [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas Longhorns]]. The Bulldogs lost the game 11\u201338 on 24 unanswered Longhorn points in the 3rd quarter.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Mississippi State Bulldogs|Season|Division|Coach|Opponent|SEC CG result}}\n|-\n| [[1998 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|1998]]\u2020 || SEC West || Jackie Sherrill || [[1998 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]] || '''L'''  14\u201324\n|-\n|}\n\u2020 Co-champions\n\n==Bowl games==\nMississippi State has played in 23 bowl games, compiling a record of 13\u201310, highlighted by wins in the 1941 Orange Bowl, the [[1963 Liberty Bowl]], the [[1999 Peach Bowl]], and the [[2011 Gator Bowl]].<ref>[http://www.hailstate.com/fls/16800/pdf/fb/fb_14orangemg.pdf?DB_OEM_ID=16800 2014 Mississippi State Football Orange Bowl Media Guide]</ref>\n\nMississippi State's first bowl game was against the Havana Athletic Club in the [[Bacardi Bowl]] on January 1, [[1911 college football season|1912]] in [[Havana, Cuba]].  Known as the Mississippi A&M Aggies at that time, the Bulldogs won by a final score of 12\u20130. Mississippi State does not count the victory against the athletic club among its bowl games and bowl wins.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bacardibowl.blogspot.com/2012/07/mississippi-m-vs-club-atletico-de-cuba.html|title=Bacardi Bowl: American Football and Cuba: Mississippi A & M vs. Club Atl\u00e9tico de Cuba (1912) |first=Michael T.|last=Wood|date=30 July 2012|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forwhomthecowbelltolls.com/2012/7/30/3200008/w-d-chadwick-and-the-bulldogs-vs-the-tigres-1912|title=W. D. Chadwick and the Bulldogs vs. the \"Tigres\" (1912)|date=30 July 2012|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1999\u20132011 Mississippi State had a 5-game winning streak in bowls. The streak ended against the [[2012 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern Wildcats]] in the 2013 Gator Bowl. The Bulldogs have been to 10 straight bowl games for the first time in school history dating back to the [[2010 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|2010 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://djournal.com/inside-msu-sports/2013/01/01/gator-bowl-pregame-bulldogs-look-to-extend-bowl-streaks/|title=Gator Bowl Pregame: Bulldogs Look to Extend Bowl Streaks|date=1 January 2013|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2014/12/orange_bowl_by_the_numbers_hig.html|title=Orange Bowl by the numbers: High-scoring, hard-running Mississippi State, Georgia Tech square off|publisher=|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hailstate.com/news/2017/12/3/football-bulldogs-headed-to-taxslayer-bowl.aspx|title=MSU Earns Eighth-Straight Bowl Bid, Will Face Louisville in TaxSlayer Bowl|publisher= MSU Athletics|accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bowl History|url=http://www.nmnathletics.com/fls/16800/pdf/fb/fb_12mg_bowls.pdf?DB_OEM_ID=16800|publisher=Mississippi State Athletics|accessdate=January 1, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150726062711/http://www.nmnathletics.com/fls/16800/pdf/fb/fb_12mg_bowls.pdf?DB_OEM_ID=16800|archivedate=July 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mississippi State Bowl History|url=http://cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/div_ia/sec/mississippi_state/bowl_history.php|publisher=College Football Data Warehouse|accessdate=January 1, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006053926/http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/div_ia/sec/mississippi_state/bowl_history.php|archivedate=October 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Mississippi State Bulldogs|Date|Coach|Bowl|Opponent|Result}}\n|-\n| [[1936 Mississippi State Maroons football team|1936]] || [[Ralph Sasse]] || [[1937 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]] || [[Duquesne Dukes football|Duquesne]] || L 12\u201313\n|-\n| [[1940 Mississippi State Maroons football team|1940]] || [[Allyn McKeen]] || [[1941 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]] || [[Georgetown Hoyas football|Georgetown]] || '''W''' 14\u20137 \n|-\n| [[1963 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|1963]] || [[Paul E. Davis]] || [[1963 Liberty Bowl|Liberty Bowl]] || [[NC State Wolfpack football|NC State]] || '''W''' 16\u201312\n|-\n| [[1974 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|1974]] || [[Bob Tyler]] || [[1974 Sun Bowl|Sun Bowl]] || [[North Carolina Tar Heels football|North Carolina]] || '''W''' 26\u201324\n|-\n| [[1980 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|1980]] || rowspan=\"2\" |[[Emory Bellard]] || [[1980 Sun Bowl|Sun Bowl]] || [[1980 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]] || L 17\u201331 \n|-\n| [[19